	<div class="sectionContainer">
		<div class="sub_section section">
			<p class="first_paragraph">
				David Bordwell and Kristin Thompson, their book <em>Film Art</em>, say that style in filmmaking consists of the patterned use of technique across a film. 
			</p>
			<p>
				The fact of the matter is that every film has a style in its technical presentation. However, there are certainly some films that we tend to think of as more “stylized” than others. The reason for this is that our sense of style as film viewers is based on convention. When the style in which a film is made conforms to the traditional technical approaches that we’re used to, the style of the film more or less “disappears.” We don’t notice it or think of it as stylized. However, the more a film’s style departs from the established conventions of storytelling technique, the more we notice the technical components and the more stylized the film seems to us. When filmmakers began using handheld cameras more frequently with the advent of lighter-weight equipment, it was initially a departure from the more traditional technical approach of shooting off a locked-down tripod. The handheld technique felt unusual and became a stylistic hallmark for some filmmakers or cinematographers. When Jean-Luc Godard began breaking from the traditional rules of editing, violating many technical rules of screen direction and incorporating jump cuts, his “style” was much more noticeable than the style of directors who continued following traditional rules. 
			</p>	
		</div>
	</div>
