<div class="eight_section_3" >
	<div class="sectionContainer">
		<div class="sub_section section">
			<h3 class="first_paragraph">STYLE IN 2001</h3>
			<p>
				Let’s take this idea of style as a patterned use of technique over the course of a film and apply it to <em>2001</em>, looking back at some of the different technical aspects of the film and thinking about what patterns we can find in Kubrick’s approach. 				
			</p>
		</div>
	</div>
	<div class="lectureQuestion">
		<%= render 'lecture_questions/show', :question => parse_lecture_question(@lecture, 3) %>	
	</div>
	<div class="sectionContainer">
		<div class="sub_section section">
			<p class="first_paragraph">
				I’ll draw attention to a few patterns I’ve noticed. 
			</p>
			<p>
				CAMERAWORK<br>
				There are a lot of static shots from a camera locked down on a tripod. Also a lot of wide angle shots. Kubrick also has the stylistic trademark of using what’s called <a href="https://vimeo.com/48425421" target="_blank">“one-point perspective”</a>, or sometimes “planimetric composition”. He often places his camera in very carefully-choreographed geometric precision with his subjects. The line of sight of the camera is placed either directly perpendicular to, or directly parallel with, the axis of the line of action in the scene (Wes Anderson uses a similar approach in a lot of his camerawork, though to very different effect). 
			</p>
			<p>
				On the other hand, there are also a number of moving camera shots at various points in the film, either in the form of a handheld camera, or carefully choreographed tracking shots.
			</p>				
			<p>
				EDITING<br>
				For one, there’s the pace of the editing. Kubrick doesn’t use a lot of quick-cuts from multiple angles to build our sense of space. He uses a lot of long takes from a single perspective that allow the action to unfold within the frame. He also occasionally makes use of cutting on graphical matching, meaning that the shots on either side of the cut both contains similar shapes on the screen. A classic example of this is the cut from prehistoric man to outer space. We see the falling bone in the first shot, then cut to the similarly-shaped floating spacecraft. Thus a cut across millennia of time––which in other contexts might be rather jarring or disorienting––is smoothed over by the graphical similarities of the imagery. 
			</p>
			<p>
				Another pattern that perhaps falls under editing is the way that Kubrick makes use of ellipses, or gaps in time. It’s something of the inverse of his approach to dwelling on long takes within a single moment. He will also cut out large chunks of time completely from the story, like the aforementioned cut with the bone or the leap from the piercing signal sent by the monolith on the moon to 18 months later aboard the spacecraft to Jupiter. 
			</p>
			<p>
				This combination of minute detail in certain scenes with leaving out whole chunks of story time suggests an approach of strategically choosing a few scenes and wringing all the detail out of them and leaving out everything else. 
			</p>
			<p>
				MUSIC/SOUND DESIGN<br>
				Again we see a few different, opposite approaches employed at different times relating to the sound design. Sometimes in the film Kubrick uses an incredibly bombastic and aggressive musical score to underline the moments occurring in the film. Then at other times, there will be long stretches of only ambient sounds (or even no sound at all!). 
			</p>
			<p>
				In all of the examples cited above, we see a similar approach that can be characterized as a synthesis of contrasts. He chooses several opposing technical approaches and employs them both at different, strategic times in the film. 
			</p>
		</div>
	</div>	
