<div class="eight_section_4" >
	<div class="sectionContainer">
		<div class="sub_section section">
			<p class="first_paragraph">
				I’ll make a few observations: one of the more obvious stylizations in this film and in the opening is Almodovar’s use of color. Many objects in the scene are colored in bright, unnatural, vibrant colors. It’s extremely unlikely that in the real world hospital equipment would be that vibrantly colored. It’s as if the colors are hyper-real. There’s also the way in which the credits are displayed. Not only are the credits similarly colorful, but they shimmer into view with a somewhat unusual and unnecessary flourish. Usually, the credits are treated as necessary but unimportant information. Here, they’re given an excess of attention. 
			</p>
			<p>
				One reason Almodovar chooses this stylized approach is that it fits the over-the-top intensity of the subject matter of the film. The film is highly melodramatic and contains a plethora of rather outlandish occurrences. The style of the film suggests that the dramatic intensity of content is almost bursting from the film’s seams, unable to be contained in the film’s materials. 
			</p>
		</div>
	</div>
